title: For Sale/Trade:  Stevens 14 1/2 Little Scout
postcontent:
Time for this one to find a new home.  Neat old gun and fun to shoot, but it doesn't fit in my collection anymore.

This gun is from before the Savage buyout of Stevens in 1920.  No serial number or date, other than the patent date of 7/2/1907. 

The finish is lacking, but this is a 100 year old rifle.  It's been used, obviously, but no damage.  The stock is as good as I've seen one one.  The buttplate appears original, not the flatter styles you see on some.  I'm sure the bore has some wear, but plenty of rifling intact and it's in good shape.

I've shot this gun on several occasions without issue.  As a disclaimer, if you are not familiar with these older falling blocks do NOT shoot high velocity ammunition out of it.  I'd recommend care shooting even standard velocity.  I've shot Federal AutoMatch out of it without any issues, but some others have resulted in bulging cases or backing out of the breach block.

I can send more pictures upon request.

I have a C&R FFL, so I will need a bill of sale with appropriate information for my bound book.  I am open to shipping to a C&R or FFL on your dime (actual shipping cost).  Open to offers if you think price is high.  Worst I can say is no thank you.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 38 Safety Hammerless.(Price drop $25.00)
postcontent:
September 20, 2014


For Sale:

Smith & Wesson Safety Hammerless New Departure or nicknamed by collectors as the Lemon Squeezer in .38 S&W CTG.

History: 32 and 38 Safety Hammerless models

The Smith & Wesson 38 Safety Hammerless models were produced from 1887 (1888 for the 32) to just before World War 2. They were chambered in either .32 S&W or .38 S&W with a five-shot cylinder. They were most often produced with a 2-inch, 3-inch, or 3.5-inch barrels; but some 6" barrelled versions are known to exist.

These top-break revolvers were designed for fast reloading and concealed carry as the hammer was internal and would not snag when dragging the revolver from a pocket. They were known as "The New Departure" to reflect the company's new approach to designing revolvers. Minor design changes were made to these revolvers over the years, resulting in several different design models, as termed by collectors. The first model was manufactured between 1887-1902. 

This is a family pass down Smith & Wesson .38 safety hammerless 5th model made from 1907 to 1940. Serial number 255XXX indicates this gun was made around 1915 and sports a 4" barrel. This gun retains literally all of the finish. The cylinder, barrel, bore, grips and frame are without visible wear. The mechanical action is tight. There is a small area of minor surface rust which is reflected in the price. Included in the sale is an antique paper box and documentation for a .22/32 Smith & Wesson Kit gun Model number 34. This was the result of another family Smith & Wesson .22 cal revolver paper box being mix up and switched over the years. There are some tools with the pistol that were used to clean a .38 cal Included is a half of a box of .38 CTG for test firing this gun and a leather clip-on holster. If you look at any internet firearm web site you will see this type of pistol being sold for well over $500.00.
Picture shows handgun with .22lr cal, .25 cal, 9 mm, .38 CTG and .38 Special.

The buyer must have a FOID card.

Will sign a bill of sale.

title: For Sale:  Stevens 14 1/2 Little Scout
postcontent:
Time for this one to find a new home.  Neat old gun and fun to shoot, but it doesn't fit in my collection anymore.

This gun is from before the Savage buyout of Stevens in 1920.  No serial number or date, other than the patent date of 7/2/1907. 

The finish is lacking, but this is a 100 year old rifle.  It's been used, obviously, but no damage.  The stock is as good as I've seen one one.  The buttplate appears original, not the flatter styles you see on some.  I'm sure the bore has some wear, but plenty of rifling intact and it's in good shape.

I've shot this gun on several occasions without issue.  As a disclaimer, if you are not familiar with these older falling blocks do NOT shoot high velocity ammunition out of it.  I'd recommend care shooting even standard velocity.  I've shot Federal AutoMatch out of it without any issues, but some others have resulted in bulging cases or backing out of the breach block.

I can send more pictures upon request.

I have a C&R FFL, so I will need a bill of sale with appropriate information for my bound book.  I am open to shipping to a C&R or FFL on your dime (actual shipping cost).  Open to offers if you think price is high.  Worst I can say is no thank you.

Open to trades.  Milsurps are what interest me most; Finn rifles, Enfields, Arisaka, Mausers, Swiss in particular, but will consider others.  I'll only consider modern firearms for local FTF trades only; bolt or lever 22's, 22 pistols, larger caliber rifles/pistols, you never know what might catch my eye.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Glock 19 Gen 4 + extras
postcontent:
Hey AL, I'm considering trading my Gen 4 Glock 19 for something new and/or different. It is currently my EDC, but I recently acquired another Glock 19 (gen 3) and considering parting with this one if the offer is right. At this time I'd rather trade for something of similar size and capacity, but offer away. Worst I can say is "No thanks, not interested." I'm very easy going so don't hesitate to let me know what you have. **I understand this is no $1000 dollar pistol, but I will ignore the $400 offers simply because of its condition and overall value. While it is not brand new, between the pistol, sights, and laser, it's value is around $900. THAT IS NOT WHAT I EXPECT TO GET, but it is why I won't sell it for the price of some SR9 or Sigma, or things of that nature. And don't even tell me I can keep my laser or sights because they don't fit the Gen 3, therefore I will have no use or want for them at that point. Also, the barrel in the pictures is not the stock barrel, but the original will be going back in. The nickel one in the pictures is from my NiB-X Gen 3 and is serialized for that pistol.**
So now, onto the firearm itself. It was purchased brand new by me about 4 years or so ago if I remember correctly. I've put around 800 or so rounds through her, and cleaned her after every range visit and periodically to keep lint buildup out of it. Slide and frame finish are basically immaculate. It currently has Trijicon Night Sights installed and a Crimson Trace laser grip. I have the OEM sights still and the 2 additional back straps that came with it. I have the original case and paper work with spent casing, and the 3 mags. Because I have my other 19, I am going to be keeping my hoster. It's nothing special anyway. 
I also have the paperwork and box for the CT grip with cleaning tips and allens for adjusting windage and elevation, as well as the OEM pin that the CT replaces in the grip. In short, I have everything needed in case you wanted to return it completely to stock. I have never done any trigger work or springs or anything, and never had a failure in any way. The only thing I did was the paint in the engravings to add a bit of contrast. Any questions, feel free to email me! 
**Not willing to travel more than maybe an hour away, no shipping, PA residents preferred,  and face to face only.
